7.1.1 - W11SR07: Lack of Visibility and Configuration Drift on Stand-alone Workstations
ISM controls:
•	1410; 1471 (Relating to the management of system configurations and software updates).
•	1494; 1495 (Relating to the identification and management of security vulnerabilities).
•	1510 (Relating to the routine assessment of system security posture).
Current Risk There is a risk that an inability to effectively manage and observe the security state of stand-alone workstations will cause significant configuration drift over time. This lack of visibility may lead to security vulnerabilities being ineffectively patched or managed, resulting in an increased risk of system compromise and the potential loss or corruption of departmental data.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
LIKELY	x	MODERATE	=	HIGH
Recommendations:
•	Implement Offline Management Tools: Deploy technical solutions designed for disconnected environments (such as Microsoft Configuration Manager with offline media or scripted baselines) to enforce consistent security configurations.
•	Establish Periodic Compliance Audits: Implement a mandatory physical audit schedule where stand-alone devices are checked against a "Gold Image" or security baseline using automated scanning tools.
•	Centralised Vulnerability Tracking: Maintain a manual or air-gapped register of software versions and patch levels for all stand-alone assets to ensure no device falls outside of supported security windows.
- Treatment #1
•	Utilise the Microsoft Security Compliance Toolkit to apply and verify hardended GPO baselines on all stand-alone endpoints.
•	Develop a robust "Sneakernet" process for the secure transfer and installation of monthly quality and security updates to disconnected systems.
•	Implement local logging and integrity checking tools (e.g., File Integrity Monitoring) to detect unauthorised configuration changes between audit cycles.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented. By establishing formal offline update procedures and a rigorous audit regime, the agency gains the necessary "observation" capability to identify and rectify configuration drift. While the management of stand-alone systems remains more resource-intensive than networked equivalents, the likelihood of unmanaged vulnerabilities leading to a compromise is reduced to "Unlikely."
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
UNLIKELY	x	MODERATE	=	MEDIUM

